<br>
It was a 2 day process.  The first day, it was in a clean, bright office.  The women were kind and helpful.  They asked me if I wanted counseling after the procedure and I said yes, because I had heard women could get messed up after they had abortions.  They told me at 7:30am the next morning, that I needed to go to a different building for the surgery.<br>
<br>
The next morning I go to this new building.  It was right smack dab in the middle of downtown Detroit.  A grey, signless building, the only one on the block.  I walk into a starch white waiting room, with no one in it.  A nurse tells my boyfriend that it will take about 3 hours.  She takes me into a back room, sticks a needle in my butt and an IV in my arm.  I soon pass out.<br>
<br>
Next thing I know I am waking up in a table in some stirrups and I feel this enormous pressure.  It hurts really bad.  I started crying and yelling that it hurt.  The doctor turns to me and says &quot;It doesn't hurt, shut up, give her some more drugs.&quot;  Then I pass out.  This was not a hallucination, I will never forget this as long as I live.<br>
<br>
When I wake up, I start crying.  I hear someone else crying, it's another girl who had the same thing done as me.  I just remember wanting my mom (who had NO clue about anything that was going on).  Finally, I was able to walk out with some help.  There was another girl there, who apparently had surgery too, but she was laughing and falling all around like in a drunken stupor.  Whoever was sent there to pick her up was laughing too, like this was an everyday thing, which right now I don't doubt that it was.<br>
<br>
Afterwards, I remember beating myself up for months.  Thinking that I was going to go to hell, that I made the wrong decision.  To this day, I still feel I made the wrong decision, but I know I am not going to go to hell, I already had my peace with God.  Oh, and that counseling that was offered me?  Yeah right, never heard from anyone, so I bought a book, heh.<br>
<br>
I'm not here to make people feel sorry for me.  I have no qualms about telling my story.  I just want everyone to know that it isn't as easy as sucking some cells out of a vacuum.  I would say that at this time, due to personal experience, that I am pro-life.  If I could turn back time, I would have gone through with the pregnancy and gave the child up for adoption or just kept it.  I don't believe any longer that abortion is a form of birth control.<br>
<br>
On the same token though, I will not tell women who get abortions they will go to hell.  That is between them and God.  I would try to talk to them as much as I could to ask them not to have an abortion, but if they chose to go through with it, I would only be a voice of support because I know what they are going through.  Three years after I had mine, my sister got pregnant and decided to have an abortion.  I tried everything I could to get her to keep it, I told her my story that I had been holding inside for 3 years, I told her she could move in with me and that I would help take care of it.  She decided to have an abortion anyway.  But I did not turn my back on her, just as I would not turn my back on any other woman who did that.  And sure enough, just as I told her, she regrets it too.  She is pregnant now, and has opted to keep it, I am really happy for her, she's got a good man.<br>
<br>
I guess what I am trying to pretty much say is don't always stereotype pro-life people, some of them may know more than you.  But I would also ask pro-life people not to turn their backs on or condemn women who make the choice to terminate pregnancy, it's not our job to judge.  That is between them and One other.<br>
